{{page-title "Documentation — Answers"}}
<div class="container mx-auto max-w-3xl py-6 px-4 space-y-6">

  <Panel::Card>
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">Answers</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      Answers are your responses to application Questions. They can be
      AI-drafted, hand-written, or a combination. You can store multiple
      versions of an answer to the same question — useful when you want to
      tailor the response for different roles or just want to keep drafts while
      you refine.
    </p>
    {{! <img src="" alt="screenshot of the answers list for a question" /> }}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Multiple Versions</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      Storing multiple answers per question lets you A/B test your phrasing,
      keep an AI draft alongside your edited version, or maintain a general
      answer and a company-specific one. Mark the best one as a
      <strong>favorite</strong>
      — it will be included in the AI's context for future generations.
    </p>
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">The Favorite Feedback
      Loop</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      Favorited answers feed back into Career Data — they're treated as writing
      samples that demonstrate your voice and communication style. Over time,
      the AI produces drafts that sound more like you and less like something
      generated. This is how Career Caddy learns your persona.
    </p>
    {{! <img src="" alt="screenshot showing the favorite button on an answer" /> }}
  </Panel::Card>

  <Panel::Card>
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">Example Answer</h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gray-50 border border-gray-200 rounded p-4 text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-2"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-500 italic text-xs mb-2">For the question: "Tell us
        about a time you improved system performance."</p>
      <p>
        We had a patient intake API at Meridian that was timing out under
        moderate load — anything above 200 concurrent requests and p99 latency
        would blow past 3 seconds. I spent a week profiling and found the
        bottleneck: every request was making 6–8 synchronous DB calls in a tight
        loop, some of which were identical lookups with no caching.
      </p>
      <p>
        The fix had two parts. First, I introduced a Redis cache for the
        lookup-heavy calls — hit rate ended up around 85% in production. Second,
        I converted the outer loop to use Celery tasks so the expensive work ran
        asynchronously and the API returned immediately. End result: p99 latency
        dropped from 1.2 seconds to 180ms, and we stopped seeing timeouts
        entirely at normal load.
      </p>
      <p>
        The lesson I took from it: profiling first, assumptions second. I went
        in thinking it was a query optimization problem; it turned out to be an
        architecture problem.
      </p>
    </div>
    {{! <img src="" alt="screenshot of an answer in the show view" /> }}
  </Panel::Card>

</div>